properties.description: Decorated pommel made out of a cetacean tooth [insert ID]. properties.description: 04/09/03Anvil made from a whale vertebra. Use-traces present on several surfaces suggest it was modified over the course of its use-life. Little of the original surface survives, but the spinal processes had been trimmed off, and both flat epiphyseal surface and the surviving outer side of the vertebra show use as an anvil in the form of green copper-staining. The vertebra is triangular in section as it survives, as two slices have been chopped off opposed sides. One resulting surface is flat, charred towards one edge, with a square socket (7.7 L, 4.0 cm deep), perhaps to hold a separate anvil, the other face is less rectangular and sloping, while one end has been crudely cut into angles sloping onto each face. One of these has a series of hollows, some with green staining and one with iron stains as well; these hollows run onto the socketed face, and are c. 5.0 cm in diameter. The sequence of use is uncertain, but it is likely that the two flat ends were used originally; when these began to show damage, the sides were split off, with the uneven side perhaps forming the base and the socketed side the working surface, the socket holding a block anvil and the small hollows used to shape material in. These hollows have damaged the end of the vertebra; erhaps at this stage it was turned again, witht he surviving outer surface used; the splitting of the uneven side could have happened at this stage, to give a triangular section which could be embedded in the workshop floor. The use-cracking of this final flat surface suggests it was at the end of its useful life. [check positioning in workshop] H (of vertebra 31.0cm) x 29.0 (original diamtere) x 19.5
